## Optimization engine — Pareto-optimal interventions

This is your second-biggest differentiator. Six intervention types to model:

Cool roofs (high-albedo coating), street trees, pocket parks, permeable pavements, urban water bodies (rejuvenated lakes — very relevant for Bengaluru), and building orientation correction for new constructions.

For each intervention in each zone, estimate three quantities: temperature reduction (ΔT in °C derived from literature + your PINN simulation), implementation cost (₹/hectare, use CPWD schedules), and equity score (weight by population vulnerability — low-income wards get higher priority).

NSGA-II minimizes three objectives simultaneously: minimize residual heat stress, minimize total cost, maximize equity coverage. The algorithm runs for ~200 generations and outputs the Pareto frontier — a curve of non-dominated solutions. You pick three representative points on the curve ("Maximum cooling," "Budget-optimized," "Equity-first") and present them as three policy scenarios.

This is the output that makes city planners lean forward. They don't want a heat map. They want to know: if I have ₹100 crore, what do I do and where?

